               <msContents>
                  <summary> The <title>Muqaddimah</title> (Preface) to the <title>Ẓafarnāmah</title>
                     (Book of Victory) composed by historian Sharaf al-Dīn ʻAlī Yazdī (d. 1454) in
                     822 AH (1419–1420 CE), and frequently referred to by another title, the
                        <title>Tārīkh-i Jahāngīr</title> (History of the World-Seizer). He later
                     completed the entire work in 828 AH (1424–1425 CE) it for the Timurid prince
                     and bibliophile, Ibrāhīm Sulṭān b. Shāh Rukh (1394–1435) in order to chronicle
                     the life and exploits of his patron's grandfather, Central Asian ruler Tīmūr
                     (b. 1336, r. 1370–1405), founder of the Timurid dynasty (1370–1507), and his
                     son and successor Shāh Rukh Mīrzā (b. 1337, r. 1405–1447). Much like this
                     manuscript, the preface does not always appear in copies of the
                        <title>Ẓafarnāmah</title> (Book of Victory), but as a separate standalone
                     work. A scribe named <persName role="scr">Qā'im Muḥammad</persName></summary>

